Another property that myocytes exhibit is variable gain.
Gain is the ratio between the amount of Ca21
released from
the SR and the amount of Ca21
entry into the myocyte that
triggers SR release. In myocytes, it has been observed that
for the same amount of triggering Ca21
, the magnitude of
release can vary as a function of the transmembrane poten-
tial. For example, in Fig. 7 A, the magnitude of ICa(L) at Vm ¼
␀10 mV and at Vm ¼ 130 mV is approximately the same,
but there is a large difference in the magnitude of the Ca21
transient at these two potentials, with the negative potential
exhibiting a larger SR Ca21
release. In Fig. 7 C we show the
simulated relationship between [Ca21
]i and ICa(L) over a
range of Vm values (indicated on the curve) and compare the
model results to experimentally measured data in guinea pig
ventricular myocytes (57). From the shape of the curve, it is

