move rapidly from the closed state (Fig. 13 D) to the open
state (Fig. 13 C) (Ca21
-dependent activation). Channels then
transition into the near inactivated states (I4 and I5, Fig. 13 F)
due to the high concentration of Ca21
in the subspace fol-
lowing SR release (Ca21
-dependent inactivation). After AP
repolarization, channels move from inactivated states I4 and
I5 to I1, I2, and I3 (Fig. 13, F and E) as subspace Ca21
decreases. From I1, I2, and I3, channels then recover to the
closed states (Fig. 13 D) as the SR stores recover. This re-
covery from inactivated to closed states is dependent on the
concentration of Ca21
bound CASQ2. As can be seen in Fig.
13 D, the delay of recovery from inactivation is longer at
slow rates than at fast rates. This is due to increased Ca21
loading of the myocyte at rapid rate, which allows faster
recovery of Ca21
-bound CASQ2 and, in turn, faster recovery
of RyR from inactivation after AP repolarization.

